@kelleyflanagan from @bachelorabc recently came on a new journey restoring coral reefs with us! Watch to see the most dramatic Coral Restoration Foundation™ dive program yet!
You can start your coral restoration journey too! Sign up for one of our weekly Dive Programs and be the change! 🔗➡️📖
.

Our team spends almost 2,000⏳hours every year battling biofoul. If we could reduce the time it takes to clean our Coral Trees, we could return more corals to the reef every year! 🎉
.
This is a chance for students to show off their engineering and design skills, and make a huge impact for corals! 
.
The winning students will receive a state-of-the-art educational aquarium for their school, from @titanaquaticexhibits 🐠🐡🐟
.

node.text:
Despite this year’s challenges, our team at Coral Restoration Foundation™ has worked nonstop to move our mission forward every single day.
.
Today our Restoration Program Coordinator, and boulder coral aficionado, Dan Burdeno, offers a look into his effort to #Restore2020 with CRF™. We hope Dan’s perspective will inspire you to help us turn this year right-side up, one coral at a time!
.
Every dollar donated to our restoration efforts on #GivingTuesday will be doubled by a generous donor who has pledged to match up to $20,000! This means that all gifts given ‪on December 1‬, will go twice as far in supporting our mission to restore coral reefs.
.
Coral reefs need your help now more than ever. Will you help us #Restore2020 ?
.
📹 : Maria McCausland/Coral Restoration Foundation™

Just a day in the life of an ocean warrior 🧜🏽‍♀️
.
Brianna, one of our recent dive program participants, put together this awesome video taking us through her entire day on a CRF™ Dive Program, from learning about the importance of coral reefs to getting out on the water and actively restoring our reef ecosystem.
.
If you've ever wondered what a CRF™ Dive Program is like, this is the video to watch 😍
.
You can also visit our website, coralrestoration.org/dive-programs to learn more 🤿
.
A big thank you to @bpatricew for creating this video and for helping us restore Florida's Coral Reef!
.
📸: @bpatricew

Only a few days until the submission deadline for the National Coral to Action Challenge! All entries must be received by Coral Restoration Foundation™ by 11:59 pm on Tuesday, February 11, 2020.
.
CRF™ is searching for a student film of one minute or less that best tells the world about the crisis facing our coral reefs and how people can help.
.
The winning film will be aired on the NBC 6 network, the “Coral to Action” Broadcast Sponsor! Together, we are giving America’s students an opportunity to amplify their message to save our planet’s coral reefs from extinction.
.
Learn more at coralrestoration.org/coral-to-action or visit our link in bio.
#reefrestoration #coralreefs #restorereefs #conservation #oceanoptimism #oceanheroes #raisethereef #coralrestorationfoundation #climateofchange

node.text:
UPDATE: We are so happy to have such an involved group of people following our page thank you all for your thoughts! This photo does in fact show new growth! This is an Elkhorn coral (A. palmata) its tips appear white because the coral tissue and skeleton are growing very fast! The color of a coral comes from a symbiotic algae living inside the coral tissue. When corals grow quickly it takes some time for the algae to “move in” resulting in white tips! 
.
Good news for our corals, no bleaching here, they are just going through a growth spurt!
.
New growth or coral bleaching? Let us know what you think in the comments!

📷 : Shane Gallimore/Coral Restoration Foundation™

node.text:
We are breaking records this #FridayFieldUpdate!
.
This July we returned a whopping 8,000 corals to the wild! That blows our previous record of 6,000 corals in one month out of the water!
.
That goal couldn't be met without dedicated restoration divers including our staff, interns, volunteers, collaborators, and dive program participants. Way to go TEAM!
 .
Speaking of teams, our summer Sea Base collaboration wrapped up this week exceeding our restoration goal of 200 corals on Alligator Reef! The Boy Scouts, with our team's guidance, returned 250 corals total! 
.
Our interns honed their teaching, harvesting, and outplanting skills in their mid-semester training and their confidence soared by the end! 
.
And finally our restoration team returned more than 1,000 corals to Pickels Reef! It is positively teeming with young corals, ready to fuse and stabilize their new home.
.
Let’s give everybody a hand for their amazing coral restoration this week! 👏👏👏 
.
📷 : Jess Levy/Coral Restoration Foundation™

It's baby making time!
.
Did you know that corals reproduce by spawning and the timing is determined by the moon cycle? 🌝 
.
This summer is a special "split-spawn" due to the two full moons taking place within one calendar month of each other. 📆 One full moon was this past week and a few restoration divers saw spawning in the wild! 
.
The next should take place during the 3rd week of August, we'll be watching in our coral nursery and hoping to see this incredible event!
.
Keep an eye out for the next full moon and another update on the split spawn 👀 
.

#FridayFieldUpdate PILLAR CORAL UPDATE: Genetic Rescue Underway!
.
A huge collaboration between scientists, aquariums, and restoration partners is providing hope for an endangered species, pillar corals.
.
Coral Restoration Foundation™ is  a contributing member of this conservation effort. We are currently caring for pillar corals in our nurseries! 
.
Last fall, we experimented with in-situ and ex-situ fragmentation in an effort to increase the population of pillar corals in our nursery. We are happy to say ALL of the pillar coral colonies are growing well since their initial fragmentation!
.
You can read the details of this ambitious undertaking through the link in our bio!

Welcome to the worlds largest coral reef restoration effort. 🌎 
.
When CRF™️ was founded in 2007 we worked with @noaa and @marinesanctuaryfdn to conserve corals broken from the reef by natural events, these are called corals of opportunity.
.
Over the years we have used science to further advance our restoration techniques and today our genetic bank is home to 481 coral genotypes, some of which have been lost in the wild.
.
We raise corals in our open ocean nurseries and return them to the wild on a massive scale, in 2020 we restored 27,293 corals! 
.
And that is how we do it.
.
🎥: Sunny Siegel/Brynne Rardin/Coral Restoration Foundation #coralrestoration #ocean #cooljobs #oceanjobs #marinebiology #marinescience #coralreef #coral #generationrestoration

BREAKING NEWS: CRF™ LAUNCHES A REVOLUTIONARY NEW TOOL FOR THE CORAL RESTORATION COMMUNITY
.
The Coral Sample Registry (CSR) is an online resource that centralizes information on coral samples collected by organizations around the world for research and restoration. 
.
Now coral scientists and restoration practitioners have a one stop shop to input information about corals they are working with! 
.
You can read all the details through the link in our bio!
.
The publication of this new tool was a collaborative effort pushed forward by Coral Restoration Consortium NOAA Coral Reef Conservation Program MyFWC Florida Fish and Wildlife SECORE International and the National Marine Fisheries Research Institute. 
.
📷 : Alexander Neufeld/Coral Restoration Foundation™
